import altair as alt

# Set a bigger default font size for plots
def bigger_font():
    return {
        'config': {
            'view': {'continuousWidth': 400, 'continuousHeight': 300},
            'legend': {'symbolSize': 14, 'titleFontSize': 14, 'labelFontSize': 14}, 
            'axis': {'titleFontSize': 15, 'labelFontSize': 12},
            'encoding': {'x': {'scale': {'zero': False}}}}}
alt.themes.register('bigger_font', bigger_font)
alt.themes.enable('bigger_font')

# Save a vega-lite spec and a PNG blob for each plot in the notebook
#alt.renderers.enable('mimetype')
alt.renderers.enable("html")

2. The Gapminder bubble chart

The "bubble chart" have become quite famous from their appearance in the Gapminder talks, and are widely used in other areas as well. Let's start by recreating a simple version of this chart ourselves!

There will be some data wrangling involved in this lab, and since 531 is primarily about visualization and this is the first lab, I will give you some hints for most data wrangling parts of this lab. Often I will link documentation or StackOverflow, so that you get practice finding information on these sources, and sometimes you will need to search them yourself if I haven't included a link.

To make this more interesting, I have compiled a more recent version of the Gapminder dataset, which contains values up until 2018 for most of the features. We will not use all the columns in the data set, but here is a description of what they contain that you can refer back to throughout the lab.

Column Description
country Country name
year Year of observation
population Population in the country at each year
region Continent the country belongs to
sub_region Sub-region the country belongs to
income_group Income group as specified by the world bank in 2018
life_expectancy The mean number of years a newborn would
live if mortality patterns remained constant
income GDP per capita (in USD) adjusted
for differences in purchasing power
children_per_woman Average number of children born per woman
child_mortality Deaths of children under 5 years of age per 1000 live births
pop_density Average number of people per km2
co2_per_capita CO2 emissions from fossil fuels (tonnes per capita)
years_in_school_men Mean number of years in primary, secondary,
and tertiary school for 25-36 years old men
years_in_school_women Mean number of years in primary, secondary,
and tertiary school for 25-36 years old women

3. Education balance

A common misconception is that women around the world go to school many years less than men. Lets find out what the data actually says about this.

Question 3.1

rubric={accuracy:2,quality:1,viz:2}

Python

  1. Compute a new column in your dataframe that represents the ratio between the number of years in school for women and men (calculate it so that the value 1 means as many years for both, and 0.5 means half as many for women compared to men).
  2. Filter the dataframe to only contain value from 1970 - 2015, since those are the years where the education data has been recorded. Again you can either create a new variable or perform the filtering as you pass the data to the plotting function.
  3. Create a line plot showing how the ratio of womens of mens years in school has changed over time. Group the data by income group and plot the mean for each group.
  4. Use layering to add a square mark for every data point in your line plot (so one per yearly mean in each group).
In[104]:
# YOUR PYTHON ANSWER GOES HERE
# Adding newe column 'ratio' = years in school woman | years in school men (1=many years for both, 0.5=half as many for women compare to men)
ratio_raw = gm["years_in_school_women"] / gm["years_in_school_men"]

gm["ratio"] = np.select(
    [
        ratio_raw.between(0.6, 1.5),   # similar
        ratio_raw.between(0.1, 0.5),    # about half
    ],
    [
        1.0,
        0.5,
    ],
    default=np.nan
)

# Filter/create new data frame to only contain value from 1970-2015 in 'year'
gm_filtered2 = gm[(gm['year'] >= 1970) & (gm['year'] <= 2015)].copy()

# plot ratio of women years in school and men years in school (y) over year (x), Group by income, plot mean for each group
gm_yearly = gm_filtered2.groupby(["year", "income_group"], as_index=False)["ratio"].mean().rename(columns={"ratio": "mean_ratio"})

gm_chartline = alt.Chart(gm_yearly).mark_line().encode(
    x='year',
    y='mean_ratio',
    color='income_group'
).properties(
    title='Women vs Men years in school (mean ratio category) over time'
)

# layering with sqaure mark for every data point in the line plot (one per yearly mean in income group)
gm_chartsquare = alt.Chart(gm_yearly).mark_square().encode(
    x='year',
    y='mean_ratio',
    color='income_group')

gm_chartline + gm_chartsquare

rubric={accuracy:2,quality:1,viz:2}

R

  1. Compute a new column in your dataframe that represents the ratio between the number of years in school for women and men (calculate it so that the value 1 means as many years for both, and 0.5 means half as many for women compared to men).
  2. Filter the dataframe to only contain value from 1970 - 2015, since those are the years where the education data has been recorded. Again you can either create a new variable or perform the filtering as you pass the data to the plotting function.
  3. Create a line plot showing how the ratio of womens of mens years in school has changed over time. Group the data by income group and plot the mean for each group.
  4. Use layering to add a square mark for every data point in your line plot (so one per yearly mean in each group). Look into the `shape` parameter for `geom_point`.
In[227]:
%%R -w 550 -h 375
# YOUR R ANSWER GOES HERE

# Adding newe column 'ratio' = years in school woman | years in school men (1=many years for both, 0.5=half as many for women compare to men)
gm <- gm %>% mutate(
    ratio_raw = years_in_school_women / years_in_school_men,
    ratio = case_when(
      between(ratio_raw, 0.6, 1.0) ~ 1.0,   # similar
      between(ratio_raw, 0.4, 0.5)  ~ 0.5,   # about half (same as your Python)
      TRUE ~ NA_real_
    )
  )

# Filter/create new data frame to only contain value from 1970-2015 in 'year'
gm_filtered2 <- gm %>% filter(year >= 1970, year <= 2015)

# plot ratio of women years in school and men years in school (y) over year (x), Group by income, plot mean for each group

gm_yearly <- gm_filtered2 %>%
  group_by(year, income_group) %>%
  summarise(mean_ratio = mean(ratio, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")


ggplot(gm_yearly, aes(x = year, y = mean_ratio, color = income_group)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point(shape = 15, size = 2) +
  labs(       # Layering with sqaure mark for every data point in the line plot (one per yearly mean in income group)
    title = "Women vs Men years in school (mean ratio category) over time", 
    x = "Year",
    y = "Mean ratio (women/men category)",
    color = "Income group"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

4. Family planning

Another common misconception is that saving the lives of children in low income countries will lead to overpopulation. Rather, lower child mortality is actually correlated with smaller family sizes. As more children survive, parents feel more secure with a smaller family size. Let's have a look in the data to see how this relationship has evolved over time.

In the plots we are going to make, it is important to note that it is not possible to tell causation, just correlation. However, in the Gapminder video library there are a few videos on this topic (including this and this one), discussing how reducing poverty can help slow down population growth through decreased family sizes. Current estimates suggest that the world population will stabilize around 11 billion people and the average number of children per woman will be close to two worldwide in year 2100.

YOUR ANSWER TO 4 GOES HERE The plots show a clear positive correlation between child mortality and the number of children per woman, especially in earlier years such as 1918 and 1938. In the early time, countries with high child mortality tend to have much larger fmaily sizes, particular in low-income groups.
Over time, from 1958 to 2018, both dhild mortality and fertility decrease across all income groups. in later years, the plots shift downward and to the left, indicating that as child mortality declines, the average number of children per woman also declines. By 2018, most countries cluster at low child mortality and smaller family sizes, regardles of income group.
This pattern supports the statement in the introduction that saving children's lives does not lead to overpopulation. Instead, the data show that lower mortality is associated with smaller family sizes, consistent with the idea that pparents feel more secure having fewer children when survival rates improve. While the plots do not establish causation, the strong and persistent correlation across time aligns with the explanation discussed in the Gapminder materials.

  3. Since we have only one value per country per year, lets create a bar chart to visualize it. Encode the CO2 per capita as on the x-axis, the country on the y-axis, and the region as the color.

In[232]:
# YOUR PYTHON ANSWER GOES HERE

## filter out the entry of co2_per_capita where it's NaN in the most recent year
latest_year = gm.loc[gm["co2_per_capita"].notna(), "year"].max()
largestCO2 = (
    gm.loc[(gm["year"] == latest_year) & (gm["co2_per_capita"].notna())]
      .nlargest(40, "co2_per_capita")
)

## plot the graph
largestCO2Chart = alt.Chart(largestCO2).mark_bar().encode(
    x=alt.X("co2_per_capita:Q", title="co2 per capita"),
    y=alt.Y('country:N').sort('-x'),
    color="region"
).properties(
    title="Highest Country CO2 per Capita"
)

  3. Since we have only one value per country per year, lets create a bar chart to visualize it. Set the aesthetics so that the CO2 per capita is on the x-axis, the country is on the y-axis, and the region is the color (you can use fill instead of color to get rid of the black outlines).

In[233]:
%%R -w 500 -h 800
# YOUR R ANSWER GOES HERE

latest_year <- gm %>%
  filter(!is.na(co2_per_capita)) %>%
  summarise(latest_year = max(year)) %>%
  pull(latest_year)

largestCO2 <- gm %>%
  filter(year == latest_year) %>%
  slice_max(co2_per_capita, n = 40)

ggplot(largestCO2, aes(
  x = co2_per_capita,
  y = reorder(country, co2_per_capita),
  fill = region
)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(
    title = "Highest Country CO2 per Capita",
    x = "CO2 per capita",
    y = "Country",
    fill = "Region"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

See this link if you want to read some background info on on when to use `geom_*` and when to use `stat_summary()`

In[313]:
%%R -w 800 -h 500

# YOUR R ANSWER GOES HERE
gm$co2_total <- gm$co2_per_capita * gm$population


ggplot(
  gm %>% filter(!is.na(co2_total)),
  aes(x = year, y = co2_total, fill = region)
) +
  stat_summary(
    fun = sum,
    geom = "area",
    position = "stack"
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Total CO2 Emissions Over Time by Region",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Total CO2 Emissions",
    fill = "Region"
  )

  color = region,
  size = population
)) +

  labs(

    x = "Children per Woman",
    y = "Life Expectancy",
    color = "Region",
    size = "Population"
  ) +
  # similar to Altair's zero=False (don't force axes to start at 0)
  scale_x_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0.02, 0.02))) +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0.02, 0.02))) +
  # make points easier to distinguish (like alt.Scale(range=...))
  scale_size(range = c(1.5, 12)) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14)
